The average particle size of the synthesized carbon nanomaterial was ∼1 nm (Fig. 2
                        ). The ζ-potential was -10.4 mV. The High-Resolution Transmission Electron Microscopy (HRTEM) analysis of CQD is shown in Fig. 3
                        . The average particle size was 1.15 ± 0.30 nm. The particles were quasi-spherical in shape (Fig. 3A) with lattice stripes (Fig. 3B), indicating their crystalline nature [15]. The line profile of lattice stripe revealed that the lattice d-spacing was 0.247 nm corresponding to the lattice fringes of graphene. Thus, the carbon atoms were graphitic sp2 hybridized carbon and the carbon nanomaterial can be classified as carbon quantum dot (CQD) with graphitic core. It mainly consisted of carbon, nitrogen and oxygen as confirmed by energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDS) spectrum of CQD (Fig. 3E). Therefore, the surface of the particles may be passivated with oxygen and nitrogen containing functional groups.
